[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have some ridiculous humanoid robot demos and a lot more. So, let\'s jump right in. First up, this AI is pretty interesting. It\'s called RecGen and this takes one or a few RGBD images,'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically normal images plus depth information, and it can reconstruct all those objects in the scene. So, here are some examples. Let\'s say this is the original image. It will first apply a'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mask to segment the objects on the table and then it will proceed to generate these 3D objects. Or here\'s an even trickier example where, you know, some of these objects are occluded. In other'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'words, they\'re blocked by objects in the front. So, the AI has very limited data on what these objects would look like at all angles. But, that\'s the strength of this AI. It\'s still able to segment everything and generate the entire'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'objects in 3D. Or here\'s another example where we can just take a photo on this table and then it will proceed to segment it and then plug it through this AI to generate all these objects in 3D. And this can generate the complete'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'geometry and textures and positions of all these objects. So, how does this work? Well, this AI is trained on a massive synthetic data set of almost 200,000 high quality 3D assets and over'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3 million synthetic RGB depth images. So, these are scenes that are heavily compositional, meaning objects are constantly rearranged or partially blocked or rotated or combined with'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other distracting stuff. And this is important for the AI to learn because the real world is messy. Objects often overlap, lighting changes, parts disappear behind other parts. So, this AI is specifically trained to do well in'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these chaotic situations. Now, if you compare this new RecGen with other competitor 3D model generators, you can see that RecGen is a lot closer to the ground truth, which is on the rightmost'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'column. You can see the positions of everything and the overall shape of all these objects are very close to the actual answer. And if you look at some quantitative results, you can see that this new RecGen also performs a lot'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'better than other competitors, both in terms of pose estimation and shape generation. Notice that here a lower means better. Same with generating objects that are severely occluded. In other words, they were blocked by other'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'objects. You can see that RecGen on average performs better than SAM3D. Note that again, the lower the score, the better. The awesome thing is if you scroll up to the top of the page, they\'ve already released the code to this. So, on this GitHub repo, it'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'contains all the instructions on how to download and run this locally on your computer. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, we have a new top open source'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image model. It\'s called HighDream 01 image by Vivigao AI. And as you can see from its generations, this is very impressive. This can generate 2K resolution images in different artistic'

[03:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'styles. It can be quite photorealistic. You can also generate images with multiple panels like this. And then here are some other diverse examples for your reference. Now, the current top open'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'source models can already do simple stuff like this, but where HighDream 01 image shines is its text rendering and infographic and poster rendering. So, for example, here is a very complicated poster. This is just one image, and as'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can see, all the text is accurate, plus the product remains consistent in the before and after. Or, here\'s another example of this live stream, and most of the text is also accurate. And then, here are some additional examples for'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your reference. So, if you need an open-source model for text rendering or generating posters with a ton of elements, then HighDream 01 image is among the best models out there you can use. You can also add a ton of different'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference images into your prompt at once. So, for example, we can plug in this kid with a ton of different items and have them all in one photo. Or, here\'s another example. Here\'s another cool example where we can plug in these'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'four faces and then add them to these specific positions in the photo, and here\'s what we get. Although, it does tend to render quite plastic-looking faces. The really cool thing about this'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is this is just one end-to-end model on raw pixels. There\'s no VAE. Now, the point of a VAE is traditionally it basically encodes and decodes the image from pixel space into latent space,'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which makes it more efficient for the AI to process. But, here they just completely got rid of this VAE. And this isn\'t just an image generator. This can also edit images semantically just like'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'NanoBanana. And this has built-in reasoning, so that\'s why this can generate more complex layouts and infographics with multiple panels and elements. And you can generate up to 2048 by 2048. Now, currently they\'ve'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'released two different models. One is just the base image model, and for this it requires 50 inference steps, so it\'s going to run a bit longer. Or, you can use the dev model, which runs a bit'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'faster, so it only requires 28 steps, but at the sacrifice of some quality. If you\'re going for quality and you don\'t care about time, then go with the full image model. If you want to generate things faster at the sacrifice of some'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quality, then go with the dev model. Both these models are 32 GB in size, so a bit bulky to be honest. You\'ll need a really high-end GPU to fit this. However, I\'m sure because this is open'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'source, there\'s going to be more quantized versions and GGUFs available very soon that can run on a lower VRAM. Now, if you look at these benchmarks, you can see that on average, Hydream 01 image even beats the previous leading'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image models like When image or Z image turbo. And even some closed models like Nano Banana 2 and SeaDream 4. If you look at this independent leaderboard by Artificial Analysis, I believe this'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hydream 01 is actually this mysterious peanut model. This is currently ranked number eight, but all the ones above it are closed source. So, at least according to this leaderboard, Hydream 01 is currently the top open-source'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image generator out there. Now, if you are interested in running this, at the bottom of the page, it contains all the instructions on how you can download and run this locally on your computer. There\'s no support from ComfyUI yet, so'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there\'s no like native ComfyUI workflow. That\'s what I\'m waiting for before I do a full installation tutorial on this. But, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week,'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we have a really powerful AI called Univid X. This is basically a video generator that can understand and generate a ton of different intrinsic features. Here\'s what I mean by that. So, not only can this AI generate normal'

[07:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'videos in RGB color, but it can also generate the albedo of that video. In other words, the base color of everything in the video. Plus, it can also generate irradiance or basically'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the lighting of the video, and it can also generate the normal or the orientation of the surfaces of the video. Not only that, but it can also detect the background and the foreground of the video. And from that, it can also'

[07:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create an alpha channel that separates the foreground from the background. And so, this allows you to do a ton of versatile stuff like removing characters or objects in a video or replacing the background with something else. Now, if'

[08:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you compare the results from this new UniVid X with other competitors in terms of normal estimation, you can see that this new one is a lot more accurate. Same with video matting, in other words,'

[08:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'separating the foreground from the background, you can see that again this new one is the most accurate. Here\'s some really cool stuff you can do with it. Again, from just one video, it\'s able to understand the albedo, the normal, and the lighting of that video.'

[08:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you add sunshine at dusk, then you can relight the scene like this. Or here\'s another example, let\'s take this video of a room. Again, it\'s able to detect all these intrinsic properties, and you can then post-process the albedo'

[08:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and normal, and then plug it through this new video, and here\'s your new results. Or here\'s another example where we can segment the foreground and the background and replace the character like this. Or here\'s another example,'

[08:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'again, segmenting the foreground and the background, and this time we can replace the background like this. So, a super flexible model that understands all these intrinsic properties of a video, which allows you to do very precise'

[09:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video edits. Now, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they have released the code to this. So, if you click on this code button and you scroll down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on how to download and run'

[09:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this locally on your computer. Notice that there\'s one model for the intrinsic properties of the video like the irradiance, the normal, and the albedo, and then another model for detecting the'

[09:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'alpha channels or basically segmenting the foreground from the background. The intrinsic model is only 800 megabytes. The Alpha model is also the same size at roughly 800 megabytes. This also uses the open-source 1.2.1 as the video'

[09:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generator, which you should be able to run on most consumer GPUs. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, Google just made their best open-source model Gemma 4'

[09:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even faster. So here\'s what they did. Specifically, they added something called multi token prediction for the Gemma 4 models. In simple terms, this lets the AI predict multiple words at once instead of painfully generating'

[10:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them one by one. This might sound small, but it solves one of the biggest bottlenecks in AI. Because here\'s the thing, modern large language models are not actually limited by raw compute power. They\'re limited by memory'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'management. Every time a model generates a single token, or basically a chunk of a word, the GPU has to constantly move billions of parameters around in memory. The processor spends a huge amount of time just waiting. And this becomes'

[10:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'especially painful on consumer hardware like laptops or phones or consumer-grade GPUs. Now Google asked a simple question. What if instead the AI could just guess ahead before the main model'

[10:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finishes thinking? This is also called speculative decoding. Instead of having one giant model slowly generate tokens at once, you pair it with a smaller, lightweight drafter model. This is in'

[11:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'charge of predicting several future tokens in advance. Now the larger original model checks the draft and if the answer is correct, then it accepts the sequence instantly, allowing it to generate multiple tokens at a time. The'

[11:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'crazy part is the output quality stays exactly the same. There\'s no downgrade in reasoning. There\'s no worse answers, but they were able to speed up the Gemma models by up to 3.1 times. That is'

[11:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty massive. So here\'s a side-by-side comparison. On the left is just the original Gemini 4 and on the right is Gemini 4 with this multi-token prediction. And as you can see, it\'s able to finish way faster at almost 80'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tokens per second. And honestly, I think this is one of the most important trends happening in AI right now. Because previously, the industry has been obsessed over making models bigger and bigger and just scaling compute. But'

[11:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'another part of the puzzle is how do we make AI faster and cheaper to run on local hardware. And I think multi-token prediction system is a great step in that direction. Awesome thing is they\'ve released these multi-token drafters for'

[12:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Gemini 4 already. So, here they released a documentation page on how you can set up Gemini 4 with this multi-token prediction. And the models are already out for you to download on Hugging Face and other places. If you\'re interested'

[12:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, we have a really interesting benchmark called Program Bench. This asks a very simple but brutal question. Can AI rebuild an entire program from'

[12:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scratch? Not just a simple bug fix or adding a simple feature, but an entire program. You see, for this benchmark, the model is given only two things: the final EXE file and its documentation.'

[12:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And it needs to code everything up based on these two things. It does not have access to any of its source code, it cannot decompile the executable, plus it cannot use the internet. It only gets'

[12:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the finished program and its goal is to code this up from scratch. And here\'s where things get interesting. The AI has to act like a real software architect. It has to test the original program,'

[13:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'figure out how it behaves, choose a programming language, design the structure, write the full code base, and produce a build script. Every decision is on the model. Now, this benchmark'

[13:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'includes 200 tasks. Some are small command line tools, others are huge software projects like FFmpeg or SQLite and the PHP compiler. To check the results, Program Bench runs more than'

[13:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '248,000 behavioral tests comparing the AI\'s rebuilt version against the original program. And the results are pretty shocking. You can see even the best of'

[13:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the best models out there including Opus 4.7, GPT-5.4 and Gemini 3.1 Pro all scored 0%. None of them could fully solve any of the 200 tasks. Although'

[14:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Opus 4.7 was able to almost resolve 3%. Still a very small percentage. But that\'s exactly the point. Program Bench is not measuring whether AI can write code snippets or fix bugs. It\'s'

[14:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'measuring whether an AI can reverse engineer an entire program including the behavior, the design systems, and rebuild the complete working software from scratch. In simple terms, this is a'

[14:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stress test for real software creation, not just coding autocomplete. And right now, the message is pretty clear. So, none of the top models are able to completely solve even one task. So, it seems like AI coding agents are getting'

[14:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more powerful. We can definitely get them to write code stuff, but building full software from scratch is still a much harder problem than it seems. Now, they\'ve released a GitHub and if you scroll down a bit here, it contains'

[14:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'instructions on how you can run this locally and test the model out yourself. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, we have a new open source model for robots.'

[15:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, this is called Mom Act 2 by Allen AI which is like one of the only open source labs in the US. So, Mom Act 2 is an Open Robotics Foundation model that\'s'

[15:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'built to reason about the world in 3D before taking action. The model is designed for real-world manipulation tasks. Now, they\'ve already released version one a few months ago, but this'

[15:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version two is a big upgrade in speed and data. Version two can make an action call in about 180 milliseconds compared to 6,700 milliseconds for the original version'

[15:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. It\'s also trained with a 700-hour bimanual robotics data set covering tasks that involve two arms, like folding towels or scanning groceries and charging phones. And the results are'

[15:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very strong. In real-world zero-shot tests, you can see that MoMo Act Two even outperforms Nvidia\'s Groot or other vision-language-action models. So, this new Open Robotics Foundation model is a'

[16:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'big shift. Robots aren\'t just getting better at moving, they\'re also getting better at understanding and reasoning about why they should move that way or how to manipulate certain objects. The awesome thing is, as with their previous'

[16:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'releases, this one is also open source. So, they\'ve already released the models on Hugging Face, so you can download these and embed them into a robot. They also plan to release the data set and the training code to this. So, this is'

[16:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'completely open source. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, we have a very useful AI for 3D generation. This is called PhysForge, and here\'s what it\'s'

[16:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trying to solve. You see, most 3D generation today can make objects that look good, but looking good isn\'t enough. If you want virtual worlds or games or simulations or robot training'

[16:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'environments, the object also has to work. So, PhysForge generates 3D assets that are not just shapes, but also physics-grounded objects. In simple terms, it tries to create things that'

[17:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know where their parts are and how these parts move, what they\'re made of, or how an agent could interact with them. The system works in two stages. First, a vision-language model acts like a physical architect. It looks at an input'

[17:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and builds a physical blueprint, like the parts, the bounding boxes, relationships, joint types, materials, mass, etc. Then, in stage two, a diffusion model turns that blueprint'

[17:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into a high-quality 3D asset with geometry, texture, and kinematic parameters. And the end result is you get 3D assets that are physically accurate and grounded. These are assets'

[17:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that have realistic joints, and they can move just like real-world objects. So, for example, they can be correctly manipulated by robotic arms. It has parts, it has constraints, and'

[18:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interaction logic. A robot can understand how to grab it, or a simulator can understand how it moves. A game, for example, would look and behave a lot more realistically. Now, if you scroll to the top of the page, they have released a GitHub repo to this. If you'

[18:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'click into it, it was only released yesterday, so they haven\'t added anything yet, but hopefully they will open source this. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also'

[18:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this week, OpenAI released their new generation of real-time voice models. These models are designed to keep up with a real conversation as it happens. Now, there are three new models that'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they released in this family. One of them is called GPT Real-Time 2, and this is a conversational voice which you can talk to in real time, just like the previous generation, but this has enhanced reasoning, and it sounds more natural. And then they also released GPT'

[18:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Real-Time Translate for live speech translation across more than 70 languages, and it can translate this into 13 output languages. And then they also have GPT Real-Time Whisper, which'

[19:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a transcription tool. So, this can listen to any audio and convert that into text in real time. So, this is great for like real-time captions or subtitles. I think one of the coolest'

[19:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'features is this GPT real-time translate. So, here\'s a really cool example of this in action. &gt;&gt; English you\'ll hear is the model\'s live audio output captured directly from this laptop with transcriptions. Now, as I start speaking in French, we\'ll lower'

[19:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the volume of my mic and increase the one from the model so you can have a real feel for it. No edits to the audio. Let\'s give it a try. &gt;&gt; What\'s really impressive is that the model can listen to me and translate'

[19:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'while I\'m speaking. It makes me think of the keyword like the verb. It will start translating right away. And the result is a much more natural conversation, just like a dialogue between two people. I can even interrupt in German.'

[19:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the model switches effortlessly between my German and your French. And we can even include technical terms like GPT, real-time, OpenAI, or computer use. And the model has no trouble handling that. &gt;&gt; Merci beaucoup, Dom.'

[20:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So, you know, each of these models have their own unique use cases. For example, GPT real-time can be used for conversational agents like in companion apps or customer support. This real-time translate is of course used for'

[20:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'translation. And then this real-time Whisper can be used for captions or meeting notes. At least for the conversational GPT real-time 2, you can see that it\'s quite a huge improvement over the previous version 1.5 across all'

[20:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these different audio benchmarks. Now, currently all these voice models are only available via their API. So, you can\'t access this in Codec or ChatGPT yet. And this is paid, so here is the'

[20:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pricing per model. Nevertheless, this is one of the best real-time voice agents you can use. So, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this page in the description below. If your'

[20:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'creative workflow feels like juggling 10 different tools just to finish one project, you should definitely check out Luma Agents by Luma AI, the sponsor of this video. Think of it as a new kind of AI workspace where AI agents actually'

[21:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collaborate with you to bring ideas to life. Not just generate outputs, but help shape the entire project from start to finish. You see, Luma agents understand the physical world behind what you\'re creating, like motion,'

[21:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'space, and how things behave. That means instead of constantly switching between tools for video, design, planning, and communication, you\'re working in one unified canvas where everything stays in context. I\'m especially impressed by how'

[21:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it handles full creative workflows. For example, you can start with a rough concept, and the agents will help develop it, organize the steps, and even route tasks across the right tools behind the scenes. The agents handle the'

[21:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'orchestration, so you can stay focused on your creative direction. In fact, it actually works best when you bring your own taste and ideas into the process. You direct the agent\'s structure, and together you can explore way more ideas'

[21:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'without getting overwhelmed by the execution. Whether you\'re a designer, content creator, or part of a creative team, Luma agents helps you spend less time managing tools and more time actually creating. Check it out using'

[22:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the QR code or the link in the description below. Next up, this AI is really cool. So, this is by Genesis AI, and they just released something called Gene 26.5.'

[22:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is basically a foundation model or a brain for robots, and this pushes them closer towards human-level physical manipulation and reasoning. We\'re not just talking about picking up boxes or'

[22:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'moving objects anymore. We\'re talking about robots that can cook a 20-step meal or make smoothies, or even do lab experiments, like working with these pipettes, or wiring cables, or even solving a Rubik\'s Cube. And heck, we'

[22:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have another demo of this robot even being able to play the piano. Now, these are the kinds of tasks that look pretty simple to humans. We\'re used to doing these already, but it\'s actually brutally hard for robots. You see, the'

[23:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'human hand is one of the most complex machines in nature. It can grip softly, twist precisely, adjust pressure instantly, and coordinate dozens of tiny movements without you even thinking'

[23:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about it. But for robots, that kind of dexterity has been one of the hardest problems in the field. Now, this new model, Gene 26.5 by Genesis, attempts to solve this. They also built a human-scale dexterous robotic hand, as'

[23:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can see in these videos, and a new data engine to train it. The idea is to capture human skills and turn them into robot data, and then scale that learning across machines. And this is really'

[23:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'important because robots are generally great at doing very repetitive factory tasks that are fixed in dimensions, but the real world is messy, right? Eggs break, wires bend, liquids spill, so'

[23:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'human hands need to constantly adapt in tiny ways. And if we can apply the same autonomous adaptation to robotic hands, then the range of possible applications for robots explodes. So, this new Gene'

