[37:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'main page in the description below. Also this week, Nvidia teases a new AI called not T-Rex, but D-Rex. And this is a new system for creating full-body digital human avatars that can move and make'

[37:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'facial expressions and also be relit from different angles, almost like a real actor standing inside a virtual studio. So, it takes a flat-looking avatar and it adds realistic lighting on top and it outputs a photorealistic'

[37:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'person that can be animated or viewed from different camera angles and placed under new lighting conditions. Normally, making a relightable human avatar is extremely hard. You have to separate the'

[37:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'person into geometry, skin reflectance, materials, shadows, and lighting. Basically, the system has to understand what the body is made of, how the light should bounce off of it, and how'

[37:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything should change when the person moves. In practice, it gets messy really quickly. You need very accurate 3D tracking and optimization, and even then expressive faces and realistic lighting are difficult to combine. But D-Rex'

[38:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes a different approach. So, here\'s the architecture, and as you can see, instead of baking relighting directly into the 3D avatar, it actually separates the problem into two parts. First, it trains an expressive full-body'

[38:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'avatar under simple white lighting. Think of this as the clean base version of the person. The body, the pose, the face expression, and the camera angle. Then, a diffusion-based video relighting'

[38:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model takes that flat render and transforms it into a version that matches a target HDR lighting setup. In other words, the avatar handles the performance and the diffusion model handles the light. The result is an'

[38:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'avatar that stays expressive while also reacting to light in a believable way. You can change the camera angle, you can change the lighting of the scene, and this avatar is able to blend in seamlessly within the scene. Now, if you'

[39:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scroll up to the top of the page, here it says the code is coming soon, so it looks like they are planning to release the code to this, which is great. Right now, if you\'re interested in reading more, I\'ll link to this page in the'

[39:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'description below. Also this week, we have a new release from Japanese AI lab Sakana AI in collaboration with Nvidia. So, they\'re working on a way to make large language models faster and lighter'

[39:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and cheaper to run, but without making them smaller. And the idea is surprisingly simple. You see, inside a transformer, a lot of computation is actually wasted because many calculations are basically zero. So,'

[39:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'instead of forcing the GPU to calculate everything anyway, here they ask a very practical question. What if we only compute the parts that actually matter? You see, the hard part is modern GPUs'

[39:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are built for dense regular math. They love big clean matrix multiplications, not messy sparse patterns where some values are ignored or maybe the shapes of things aren\'t consistent. In fact, if'

[40:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you want to learn more about the technical details of how a transformer actually works, definitely see this video if you haven\'t already. Anyways, to solve this issue, the team built a new sparse format called 12, which'

[40:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stands for tile-wise L pack. Plus, they also developed a set of custom CUDA kernels designed for NVIDIA GPUs to do this unique processing. It\'s some really complex math, but think of it like'

[40:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'packing only the useful pieces of the model\'s internal activity into the GPU. So, the hardware can skip wasted work without getting slowed down. And the results are pretty impressive. So, for large language models running on H100'

[40:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'GPUs, they reported over 30% speed-ups in inference and over 30% reduction in energy savings. That\'s pretty insane. And same with training, this new'

[40:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'architecture was able to speed up training by over 20% and also reduce memory usage by over 20%. The impressive part is that the model keeps roughly the same downstream performance while becoming much more efficient. So, if'

[41:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this kind of sparsity becomes practical at scale, it could make powerful LLMs cheaper to run and faster to serve, and also waste less energy. And here it says, "We will release and open source all of the kernels to facilitate future'

[41:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'research." So, if you click on this link and you scroll down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on how you can set this up and run it on your computer. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this page'

[41:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the description below. Next up, this AI is pretty cool. It\'s called Swift I2V, and this can turn a single image into a high-resolution video. And the main breakthrough is efficiency. You see, image-to-video models have gotten'

[41:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much better, but generating a video at 2K resolution is still brutally expensive. You either generate the whole thing at high resolution, which would take an enormous amount of compute and time, or you can generate a'

[41:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lower-resolution video and upscale it later. But, the upscaler often causes some weird details or artifacts or other inconsistencies. Now, Swift I2V tries to get the best of both worlds. So, it'

[42:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes an input image and it can output up to an 81-frame video at 2K resolution. And here\'s how it works. First, it creates a low-resolution motion reference. Basically, a rough'

[42:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version of how the scene should move. Then, in the second stage, it refines that motion into a full 2K video while still using the original image as a strong guide. Think of it like sketching the movement first, then painting a'

[42:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'final video in high detail. The clever part is something called a conditional segment-wise generation. Instead of trying to process the entire high-resolution video at once, it splits the video into smaller time segments'

[42:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'while still letting nearby segments share context so the video doesn\'t fall apart. This keeps memory under control, which is why they say that this can run on just a single RTX 4090 within 24 GB of VRAM while reducing the total compute'

[43:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time by 202 times, which is pretty insane. Now, if you compare the results of this new SwiftITV with other high-resolution methods or video upscaler methods, you can see that this'

[43:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new one is way more detailed and accurate. The rest of the competitors tend to mess up the face of the portrait. Sin a scale actually is pretty good, but it completely ignores the camera movement from the original video.'

[43:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, here SwiftITV is noticeably better. And then, here\'s another example for your reference. At the top of the page, they have released a GitHub repo, and if you scroll down a bit, here it says that they are planning to release the'

[43:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inference code and the models to this. So, stay tuned for that. For now, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, we have a new image acceleration method called continuous time distribution'

[43:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'matching or CDM for short. This is from Alibaba, and this is all about making diffusion image models much faster while maintaining image quality. You see, normally diffusion models create images'

[44:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'by taking many small denoising steps. It basically starts with an image of random noise, and then it gradually takes away some of that noise at every step until you get your final image. And this requires usually 20 to 50 steps. But'

[44:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with this method, it only requires four steps while keeping similar quality. So, that\'s like speeding things up by five times. So, here are some examples where we apply CDM to Stable Diffusion 3. Or'

[44:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here\'s another example where we apply this to long cat image. And as you can see, the quality is still very good at only four steps. Now, previously, we\'ve had other accelerators that can also get'

[44:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an image model to generate things in only four steps. The most famous ones are DMD. However, you can see that this new CDM is a lot more detailed. Here are some additional examples for your'

[44:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference. If you compare CDM with DMD2, you can see that CDM is just way more detailed and defined, whereas DMD2 looks very plastic. In fact, if you look at these results, then across all these different benchmarks, including'

[45:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aesthetics and image quality, it even beats DMD. So, this makes it currently the best acceleration method for image generation. And with this speedup, if you have a decent GPU, this means you can generate images in just a few'

[45:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'seconds, almost in real time, and the quality actually looks great. Now, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they have released support for Stable Diffusion 3 and long cat. Hopefully, there will also be support for the'

[45:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leading open models out there like Z Image or Kwen or Flex Kline as well. If you click on this code button and you scroll down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on how to run and use this on your computer, as well as how to'

[45:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'train this yourself. For now, if you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, Microsoft drops a pretty interesting AI called Map to World. In simple terms, it can generate'

